In a '''low-IF receiver''', the [[Radio Frequency|RF]] [[Signal (electrical engineering)|signal]] is mixed down to a non-zero low or moderate [[intermediate frequency]], typically a few [[Hertz|megahertz]] (for TV), and even lower frequencies (typically 120-130kHz) in the case of FM radio band receivers. Low-IF receiver topologies have many of the desirable properties of [[zero-IF receiver|zero-IF architectures]], but avoid the [[DC offset]] and [[1/f noise]] problems.

The use of a non-zero IF re-introduces the [[Image response|image issue]]. However, when there are relatively relaxed image and neighbouring [[Electronic selectivity|channel rejection]] requirements they can be satisfied by carefully designed low-IF receivers. Image signal and unwanted blockers can be rejected by [[quadrature downconversion]] (complex mixing) and subsequent [[Electronic filter|filtering]].

This technique is now widely used in the tiny [[Frequency modulation|FM]] receivers incorporated into [[MP3]] players and [[mobile phone]]s and is becoming commonplace in both [[Analog television|analog]] and [[Digital television|digital]] TV receiver designs. Using advanced [[Analog signal processing|analog-]] and [[digital signal processing]] techniques, cheap, high quality receivers using no [[resonant circuit]]s at all are now possible.

